owned political scientist Cynthia Enloe exposes the workings of everyday patriarchy-in how Syrian women civil society activists have been excluded from international peace negotiations; how sexual harassment became institutionally accepted within major news organizations; or in how the UN Secretary General's post has remained a masculine domain. Enloe then lays out strategies and skills for challenging patriarchal attitudes and operations. Encouraging self-reflection, she guides us in the discomforting curiosity of reviewing our own personal complicity in sustaining patriarchy in order to withdraw our own support for it. Timely and globally conscious, The Big Push is a call for feminist self-reflection and strategic action with a belief that exposure complements resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aFeminismxSocial conditions. 0aPatriarchyxHistory. 0aPatriarchyxSocial aspectszSyria. 0aPatriarchy. 0aSex role. 0aSexual harassment. 0aWomenxEconomic conditions. 4agender womens studies. 4alesbian rights. 4algbt rights. 4amale allies. 4apatriarchal society. 4apatriarchy. 4apresidential election. 4arape kits. 4asecretary general of the un. 4aself reflection. 4asexual harassment. 4awomens rights advocate. 4awomens rights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520969193zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520969193.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c201